\subsection{Distinction from Eddington}

Several attempts exist to derive $\alpha$ from first principles. Eddington~\cite{eddington1946} sought to derive $\alpha^{-1} = 136$ (later revised to $137$) from pure combinatorics, but was judged to be numerology for three reasons: (i)~suspicion that the result was known in advance and reverse-engineered, (ii)~no structural consistency check, (iii)~no necessity for the axiom choice. Koide~\cite{koide1983} found a numerical coincidence in lepton mass ratios but could not provide its origin. The noncommutative geometry of Connes~\cite{connes1996} sought to derive physical constants from symmetry structures. Lisi's $E_8$ theory~\cite{lisi2007} was refuted by Distler and Garibaldi~\cite{distler2010}.

Bars' 2T-physics~\cite{bars2006} uses the signature $(d,2)$, and for $d=5$ the same $\mathrm{SO}(5,2)$ as in this paper appears. However, Bars' $(5,2)$ is a spacetime signature with two time axes, whereas $(5,2)$ in this paper is the signature of a quadratic form arising from the irreversible/reversible classification of the 7 internal CAS degrees of freedom. In Bars' theory the second time axis is removed by an $\mathrm{Sp}(2,\mathbb{R})$ gauge symmetry, recovering $(d-1,1)$ physics; in the present system the 2 reversible axes (observer, superposition) are the zero-cost reference paths of CAS and are not removed by a gauge symmetry. The two constructions use the same group $\mathrm{SO}(5,2)$ but differ fundamentally in physical interpretation. Bars did not arrive at a derivation of $\alpha$.

The most precise measurement of $\alpha$ was performed by Morel et al.~\cite{morel2020} with an uncertainty of $81$\,ppt.

The present approach differs in all three respects:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Rather than ``importing'' the Wyler formula, the signature is first determined by Theorem~\ref{thm:cost-signature} and the Wyler formula is its consequence.
\item There is a structural consistency check in $\sin^2\theta_W$ (Section~\ref{sec:prediction})---an independent structural verification that Eddington could not provide.
\item The axiom choice stems from the single principle ``every change in the universe is an atomic operation that incurs cost.'' Eddington's 16-fold symmetric algebra was criticized as having been chosen to reproduce the target number $137$ rather than being physically motivated; the axioms of the present system originate from the independent principles of causality preservation + minimum cost.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Self-positioning.} Historically, theories that attempted an axiomatic derivation of $\alpha$ have been judged to have failed. The specific contributions by which this paper distinguishes itself from previous attempts are threefold: (i)~prior derivation of the signature (Theorem~\ref{thm:cost-signature}), (ii)~independent verification via $\sin^2\theta_W$, (iii)~blocking numerology through search-space restriction (Section~\ref{sec:discussion}). Whether these contributions suffice to overcome the historical pattern of failure is a matter for the community to judge.

